awe : Lazarus! Come Forth! I love the pensive mix of browns and tans. The use of shadows lends a pensive tone to the whole piece. The subject, Lazarus, is painted as a muscular individual--his fingers grip a rock and his whole arm tightens. I can see his toes digging into the rubble. The knee on the rock adds to the grounding effect. It is so easy to get lost in this piece and forget is a 2-dimensional canvas. The shroud is red, likely a compliment to the browns and tans of the piece. The expression as the subject looks toward the light is one of gratitude. The skull in the back identifies the location as a graveyard, but the hourglass had not been invented yet. The squares to the left look like the hinges were broken off from the inside--by Lazarus himself. A very powerful piece.
